<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>         3.)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Druid nukes in PoP are rather odd.  First off, they don't get any (besides a dinky stun) until 64.  Second, their lvl 64 nuke is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>         worse</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than Moonfire--which shows you exactly how <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>         good</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Moonfire is.  Finally, at lvl 65 they get a better nuke than Moonfire, but only by a very small amount.  This will not be the favorite expansion of Evocation Druids, I predict.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     4.)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Insanity (Enchanter) is well.. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>     insane!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  It has better ratio than all Magi nukes, with the single exception of FoT.  It is equal or better ratio than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>     all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Druid nukes.  It is more effecient than every SoL/PoP Wizard nuke, save GSS.  Simply put:  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     WTF?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Ratio nukes have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>     never</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> been an Enchanter forte.  In fact, damaging spells of any kind were never exactly a primary role for Enc's.  They only have two lines: ineffecient Magic DD w/long recast, and Magic DoT w/debuff.  In PoP, suddenly Enc get a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>     very</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> effecient nuke, and the debuff component of their (new) DoT appears to have been removed to allow stacking.  Suddenly the mild-mannered 'chanters are now pime-time damage dealers?  Don't give me the old &quot;but it has a long recast!&quot; line, simply chain alternate with another spell like Wizards do with ISoS/A<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> oI.  For instance, you could chain Insanity/A:CV and get ~120.6 DPS whilst achieving a 3.73 ratio. There's no problem with how much damage Insanity does, the problem is with the ratio.<br>
